SIMPLE: foresee
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Foresee
<hw>Fore*see"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>forese⟦oacute⟧n</ets>; <ets>fore + se⟦oacute⟧n</ets> to see. See
<er>See</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To see
beforehand; to have prescience of; to foreknow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prudent man <qex>foreseeth</qex> the evil.</q> <rj><qau>Prov.
xxii. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To provide.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great shoals of people, which go on to populate, without
<qex>foreseeing</qex> means of life.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foresee</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Foresee
<hw>Fore*see"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To have or exercise
foresight.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>foreseeable</ent>⟦br⟧
